	abstract = {CMB observables have largely fixed the expansion history of the universe in the deceleration regime and provided two self-calibrated absolute standards for dark energy studies: the sound horizon at recombination as a standard ruler and the amplitude of initial density fluctuations.  We review these inferences and expose the testable assumptions about recombination and reionization that underly them.  Fixing the
